:: After the Gully {"position":"950,275","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://siko91.github.io/Jebe-s-Coming-Of-Age-Hunt/assets/images/6.jpg" style="max-width:80%">

The gully finally opens. The steep black walls fall away and sunlight—thin, pale, but welcome—spills across a flat shelf of rock and ash. Jebe guides the mare to the sunlit patch, lets her stand, and swings down from the saddle. He stretches his back, rolls his shoulders, and takes a long swallow from his water skin. The mare lowers her head to lip at a sparse patch of dry grass that has somehow survived here.

For a few minutes there is only the sound of wind moving through stone and the soft crunch of the horse grazing.

<<if $spirit_warning is true>>
Jebe glances upward for a moment, as if searching the empty sky.

“…Thank you,” he says quietly, almost grudgingly. “For the warning back there.”

He shakes his head once, as though surprised at his own words, then turns his attention forward again.
<<set $spirit_warning to false>>
<</if>>

Then the voice returns—clear, close, insistent.
<<switch $spirit_type>>
<<case "revenge">>
The words arrive sharp and eager:

“This gully is perfect for ambushing Temur. Set a trap here—poisoned stakes, loose rocks, anything. End him before he ends you.”

Jebe freezes mid-step. His hand tightens on the water skin. He stares at the narrow mouth of the gully they just left, as though he can see Temur riding through it already.

He exhales slowly.

“Traps with poison are for the weak and the cowarly,” he says aloud, voice low and firm. “I am neither.”

He turns his back on the gully and pats the mare’s neck once.

“Temur may be my enemy, but I will not dishonor myself—or the hunt—to kill him like a rat in a snare.”

<<case "sorrow">>
The voice comes soft, almost trembling:

“You should have chosen a safer path. This risk was unnecessary. You could have been hurt… or worse.”

Jebe pauses. He looks down at the ash under his boots, then up at the open sky again. His brow furrows.

He speaks quietly, as if answering a person standing beside him.

“The prey’s trail leads here. If I turn away every time the path grows hard, I’ll catch nothing at all.”

He adjusts the quiver on his back.

“I want the glory of catching a good prey—not just surviving. Glory doesn’t come from the safest road.”

<<case "trickery">>
The voice slides in smooth and tempting:

“The prey you are chasing is small and insignificant. I can lead you to a more impressive one—bigger tracks, richer reward. Why waste time on scraps?”

Jebe stands very still for a long moment. His fingers drum once against the curve of his bow.

Then he shakes his head.

“I’m not in a hurry,” he says. “Catching a small prey now doesn’t mean I cannot catch a bigger one later.”

He looks out across the wasteland ahead, eyes narrowing against the light.

“Besides… I don’t trust easy promises.”

<</switch>>

Jebe takes one last breath of the thin, sun-warmed air, then swings back into the saddle. The mare snorts and steps forward eagerly.

The hunt continues.

