:: Departure from the Threshold {"position":"350,275","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://siko91.github.io/Jebe-s-Coming-Of-Age-Hunt/assets/images/2.jpg" style="max-width:80%">

The drumbeats fade behind you as fifty ponies break into a steady canter. The village recedes quickly—felt yurts shrinking to dots, the shaman’s raised hand a final silhouette against the morning sky.

Jebe rides near the middle of the loose pack, not at the front showing off, not at the rear hiding. His bay mare moves with sure-footed ease, her hooves kicking up small puffs of dust that catch the light. The wind already carries the faint metallic scent of ash.

The green steppe thins beneath them. Grass grows sparser, shorter, giving way to patches of pale soil. Then the color bleeds out entirely. Ahead the world turns monochrome: endless rolling dunes of fine gray ash, broken by jagged black rock spines and the occasional twisted skeleton of a long-dead tree.

The other boys shout to one another—half bravado, half nerves. Someone sings a snatch of an old hunting song, but it dies quickly against the empty horizon. Temur rides at the front now, shoulders squared, glancing back once toward Jebe with a look that promises nothing good.

Jebe keeps his eyes forward. His painted face is set, jaw tight. He adjusts the quiver on his back, checks the bow case tied to his saddle, pats the small bundle of dried meat and water skin. Every motion is deliberate, practiced. He is ready. He believes he is ready.

You drift beside him, unseen, a cool breath against his ear that he has not yet learned to recognize.

The last stripe of green disappears under the ponies’ hooves.

The Ashen Wastelands swallow them whole.

