:: First Prey Attempt: The Horned Hare Chase {"position":"1100,275","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://siko91.github.io/Jebe-s-Coming-Of-Age-Hunt/assets/images/7.jpg" style="max-width:80%">

The sun climbs higher, bleaching the ash to a dull silver. Jebe’s eyes catch movement—a flicker of white and tan against the gray.

A horned hare bursts from behind a cracked boulder, ears flat, horns glinting like polished bone. It is larger than the village rabbits, lean and fast, built for this merciless ground. It darts low and erratic, zigzagging between stones.

Jebe’s breath sharpens. This is no scavenger’s meal; this is worthy.

He urges the mare into a controlled canter. She responds instantly, hooves finding purchase on the uneven rock without hesitation. Jebe rises in the stirrups, weight forward, bow already in hand. He nocks an arrow in one fluid motion—feathers fletched from steppe eagle, shaft smoothed by his own knife.

The hare veers right. Jebe follows, guiding the mare with knees alone. Wind tears at his face, stinging the painted lines. The hare leaps a low ridge; Jebe matches it, the mare gathering and surging.

He draws. The bow creaks. String bites his callused fingers. He tracks the hare’s rhythm—three bounds, pause, veer—waits for the instant it straightens.

Release.

The arrow flies clean, a dark line against the pale sky. It strikes true, just behind the shoulder. The hare tumbles, rolls once, and lies still.

Jebe reins in hard. The mare slides to a stop in a spray of ash. He swings down, approaches slowly, respectfully. The hare’s sides still heave once, twice—then stop.

He kneels. Draws his small ritual knife. Touches the blade to the creature’s throat in the old way—quick, clean, a murmured word of thanks to its spirit for the gift of its life and strength.

Blood soaks into the ash, dark and brief. Jebe ties the small carcass to his saddle with quick, practiced knots. It is not the greatest prey, but it is his first. A beginning.

He stands for a moment, looking out across the broken plain. The wind carries no sound of other hunters. Only silence, and the weight of what comes next.

