:: Initial Scouting: Reading the Terrain {"position":"650,275","size":"100,100"}
<img src="https://siko91.github.io/Jebe-s-Coming-Of-Age-Hunt/assets/images/4.jpg" style="max-width:80%">

The voice fades as quickly as it came, leaving only the low whistle of wind through cracked rock.

Jebe’s shoulders tense. He glances over one shoulder, then the other, as if expecting to catch sight of whatever just spoke inside his head. His lips press into a thin line.

“Another liar,” he mutters, voice low enough that only his mare hears. “Or a fool. Either way—keep your words. I don’t need them.”

He exhales sharply through his nose, almost a snort of dismissal, then swings down from the saddle in one smooth motion. His boots sink half an inch into the soft ash. The mare snorts and shifts her weight, ears flicking at the sudden quiet.

Jebe crouches beside a shallow depression in the gray dust. Fresh tracks—small, cloven, hurried—cross the surface like hurried scratches. A horned hare, perhaps, or something similar. Nearby, a scattering of droppings still holds a trace of warmth. He brushes ash aside with gloved fingers, revealing the faint imprint of paws that veered left toward a low ridge of black stone.

The wind picks up, carrying fine grit that stings his cheeks and makes his painted lines feel tight against his skin. He squints into the distance. Nothing moves except dust devils spinning lazily across the flats. No other riders in sight. No smoke. No sound but the hiss of ash on rock and his own steady breathing.

For the first time the full weight of the hunt settles on him—not the ceremony, not the drums, not the shaman’s blessing, but the simple, brutal fact: out here, no one will come if he calls.

He straightens slowly, one hand resting on the curve of his bow. His eyes scan the horizon again, wary, but not afraid.

Jebe whispers: "Not far... Through the gully."

